1Ô∏è‚É£ Select all columns
Q1. Write a query to display all columns from the Employees table.
Answer
sql
SELECT * FROM Employees;
2Ô∏è‚É£ Select specific columns
Q2. Display only name and salary from the Employees table.
Answer
sql
SELECT name, salary
FROM Employees;
3Ô∏è‚É£ Using WHERE clause
Q3. Select employees whose salary is greater than 40000.
Answer
sql
SELECT *
FROM Employees
WHERE salary > 40000;
4Ô∏è‚É£ Using aliases
Q4. Display employee name as EmployeeName and salary as MonthlySalary.
Answer
sql
SELECT name AS EmployeeName,
       salary AS MonthlySalary
FROM Employees;
5Ô∏è‚É£ Using DISTINCT
Q5. Display unique job titles from the Employees table.
Answer
sql
SELECT DISTINCT job_title
FROM Employees;
6Ô∏è‚É£ Using ORDER BY
Q6. List all employees sorted by their salary in descending order.
Answer
sql
SELECT *
FROM Employees
ORDER BY salary DESC;
7Ô∏è‚É£ Using BETWEEN
Q7. Select employees whose salary is between 30000 and 50000.
Answer
sql
SELECT *
FROM Employees
WHERE salary BETWEEN 30000 AND 50000;
8Ô∏è‚É£ Using IN operator
Q8. Select employees who work in departments 10, 20, or 30.
Answer
sql
SELECT *
FROM Employees
WHERE department_id IN (10, 20, 30);
9Ô∏è‚É£ Using LIKE
Q9. Select employees whose name starts with 'A'.
Answer
sql
SELECT *
FROM Employees
WHERE name LIKE 'A%';
üîü Using LIMIT / TOP
Q10. Display the first 5 employees.
Answer
MySQL / PostgreSQL / SQLite:
sql
SELECT *
FROM Employees
LIMIT 5;
SQL Server:

sql
Copy code
SELECT TOP 5 *
